### Properties in C#

Properties are members that provide a flexible mechanism to read, write, or compute field values. They combine the functionality of fields and methods.

### Auto-Implemented Properties

The simplest form, introduced in C# 3:

```csharp
public class Person
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Age { get; set; }
}
```

### Full Property Declaration

```csharp
private string name;

public string Name
{
    get { return name; }
    set { name = value; }
}
```

### Read-Only Properties

```csharp
// No set accessor
public string FullName { get; }

// Expression-bodied (C# 6+)
public string Greeting => $"Hello, {Name}";

// Init-only setter (C# 9+)
public string Id { get; init; }
```

### Computed Properties

```csharp
public class Rectangle
{
    public double Width { get; set; }
    public double Height { get; set; }

    // Computed property (no backing field)
    public double Area => Width * Height;

    // Expression-bodied getter
    public double Perimeter => 2 * (Width + Height);
}
```

### Property Validation

```csharp
private int age;

public int Age
{
    get { return age; }
    set
    {
        if (value < 0 || value > 150)
            throw new ArgumentException("Age must be 0-150");
        age = value;
    }
}
```

### Private Set

```csharp
public string Name { get; private set; }  // Public get, private set
```

### Static Properties

```csharp
public static class Config
{
    public static string AppName { get; set; } = "MyApp";
    public static int MaxUsers { get; } = 100;
}
```

### Property Modifiers

| Modifier | Effect |
|----------|--------|
| `virtual` | Can be overridden in derived class |
| `override` | Override a virtual property |
| `abstract` | Must be implemented in derived class |
| `sealed` | Cannot be overridden further |
| `static` | Belongs to the type, not instances |

### Required Properties (C# 11+)

```csharp
public class Product
{
    public required string Name { get; init; }
    public required decimal Price { get; init; }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Properties are accessed like fields but implemented like methods. Use auto-implemented properties for simplicity, full properties when validation or logic is needed. Use `init` for immutable properties set during initialization. Use `required` (C# 11+) for mandatory properties.

### Field-Backed Properties (C# 13 Preview)

```csharp
public class Person
{
    public string Name { get => field; set => field = value; }
}
```

codeExample:
using System;

public class BankAccount
{
    public string AccountNumber { get; init; }
    public string Owner { get; set; }

    private decimal balance;
    public decimal Balance
    {
        get { return balance; }
        private set { balance = value; }
    }

    public void Deposit(decimal amount)
    {
        if (amount > 0)
            Balance += amount;
    }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var account = new BankAccount
        {
            AccountNumber = "123-456",
            Owner = "Alice"
        };
        account.Deposit(1000);
        Console.WriteLine($"Balance: {account.Balance:C}");
    }
}
